The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has issued warnings for colored people traveling to Missouri based on discriminatory state principles and racist attacks.
“The NAACP Travel Recommendation for Missouri, effective August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors and residents of Missouri to pay increased attention when traveling across the state as a result of a series of disputed racially motivated incidents currently occurring across the state,” the association said in a statement.
The NAACP said it took this step on the basis of current Missouri laws that make it difficult to defend racist-motivated acts before a court, as well as as a result of the actions of law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities.
“Civil rights are being violated.
People are stopped by police just because of their skin color, they are attacked or killed," Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP, told the Kansas City Star.
"We have the largest number of complaints so far."
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization to the U.S. state.
Among the incidents cited by the organization were racially motivated insults directed at black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in disputed circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while traveling across the state and was taken into custody by police without being charged with a crime.
The travel recommendation also draws attention to a recent statement by the Missouri Attorney General’s Office, which states that black drivers are 75% more likely to be stopped by police.
“The purpose of the travel recommendation is to alert people and warn their families, friends and coworkers about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared – they should bring money with them to pay bail, or let their relatives know they’re going to travel the country.”
According to current FBI reporting numbers, there were 100 cases of hate crime in Missouri in 2015, ranking the state 16th among all states.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that makes it difficult to sue a company for discrimination in providing accommodation or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel recommendations for Texas and Arizona after states passed an immigration law that allows government officials to detain people on the grounds of violating the law, which the ACLU says is meant to improve racial profiling.
Travel recommendations are usually issued by the State Department for foreign countries, but lately advocacy groups have resorted to these measures in response to specific laws and trends within the US.
