In fact, he rarely uses a pan.
In her wooden hut, located in the capital city of Paniai Enarotali in the Indonesian province of Papua, a woman usually simply throws a sweet potato - in the language of the local "note" - directly into the fire.
After half an hour, he removes the potato and tastes it with unwashed hands.
The bard sits on muddy ground - the house is not equipped with furniture - where he also performs his daily tasks, such as washing his laundry in muddy water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket in a room without a roof replaces the toilet.
As the youngest of her husband’s four wives, she was not assigned any fields to cultivate.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late at night poses a danger: most of the men in the village are unemployed and often drink alcohol. In addition, soldiers are stationed in the village.
"After five o'clock in the afternoon, no one dares to wander around the village," says Bardina.
It is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was declared part of Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 elders were forced to vote in the form of a public hand-lift in front of the occupying army.
The current anti-Dutch protest movement quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which ruled the entire region except for foreign journalists or civil rights watchdogs.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua - an independent Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is such a remote and devastated city, which can be reached after a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire, and then a five-hour stomach-clutching ride.
Public transport does not work at this place.
The city of 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, roofs made of woolen sheets in shades of gray and rusty color.
Very few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and virtually no foreigners had ever visited this place.
Before the arrival of Christians, locals worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
"We weren't used to wearing this dress," Bardina says, pointing to her colorful, hand-knit turban, dark T-shirt, and shiny skirt.
"We used to wear only leaves."
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province – 28% of the population lives below the poverty line and its child mortality and literacy rate is one of the worst in all of Asia.
It is also the gold of Indonesia.
The world’s largest and most lucrative gold mine, Grasberg, owned by the Freeport McMoran Company of the U.S. Phoenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai – a rocky province roughly the size of New Jersey, home to about 153,000 residents.
In 2015, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua supports logging with an estimated value of $78 billion.
However, these riches are a source of suffering for the Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian army.
An investigation conducted by the New York Times in 2005 found that Freeport paid local military officials and units about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 for a single officer.
Papuans calling for self-government threaten this golden goose and are therefore severely suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969 and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
The massacres in the tribal area of Papua during the 1970s amounted to genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes the atrocities that took place last year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture — according to another report, electrocution and rape are particularly popular — and the brutal repression of peaceful protesters.
“It’s hard to count the number of casualties because incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The situation was aggravated by the fact that Papuan resources attracted colonists to Indonesia.
Of the province's 3.5 million inhabitants, 83% profess Christianity, but the demographics change with the influx of Muslim immigrants from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, or a mixture of vegetables with peanut sauce.
The locals are fighting for survival.
“Immigrants have started selling chickens and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,” explains 24-year-old Abeth You, who was born in Paniai and moved to the provincial capital of Jayapura to work.
"The natives of Papua - mother-mother (women) - thus lost their jobs."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, promised in his 2014 presidential campaign to address inequality and rights violations.
The former carpenter also secured his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta in 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But very little has changed in Papua and the local people feel betrayed.
“Our hearts were broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokpwi in the hope that he would listen to our call for justice,” You said.
The fact is that just two months after Jakowi’s inauguration in October, Paniai experienced a great shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children sang Christmas songs at a campfire in the town of Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on motorcycles emerged from the darkness of the night.
Two of the surprised children told them to turn on the lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by this rebuke and the tone with which it was spoken, and later returned with four other soldiers, said local parish priest Yavedt Tebai.
Two of the soldiers in a drunken state chased a group of children and beat them with their guns, according to victims and witnesses of the incident.
One of the soldiers then fired on a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
Hours later, a nearby election commission building was set on fire, and the next day things escalated.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on a football pitch in front of a local police station and army headquarters to demand justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed a waita dance - in which they run in a circle and imitate the singing of birds - of the Papuan tribe Mee Pago.
Several protesters began to throw stones at buildings.
As tensions intensified, the soldiers received an order via radio: “If the crowd tries to resist at least three times, you are allowed to shoot,” according to an official document published by TIME, the content of which was never published in local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, head of the Enarotali district of Kego Koto, recognized the impending danger and urged residents to disperse to their homes.
But no one paid attention to his words.
"When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist," he told TIME on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who the shooter was, but he said the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
"There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting," he added.
One local resident, Alfius Youw, was shot three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran to the body to make sure it was really him,” Yohanes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
A Papuan police inspector, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were only “securing” the station that was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten us with death,” said a spokesman for the Papuan police, Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many escaped with injuries.
The news of the killings spread through the Jakarta media the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing his sympathy for the families of the victims and promising to deal with violence in Papua.
“I demand an immediate solution to this problem so that it never happens again,” he said.
National Security Minister Wiranto announced in October 2016 that he would introduce an extrajudicial mechanism to resolve past violent acts.
Almost immediately, however, the excuses began to sound.
“Most of the violence happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the 1990s and some at the beginning of the 21st century.
I mean, we are determined to punish these acts of violence, but it will not be an easy task," he said.
In an interview with TIME in Jakarta on June 5, Wiranto said he had no plans to introduce any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said, “all cases will be brought to court.”
Wiranto, who has been accused by the UN of "crimes against humanity" based on more than 1,000 deaths during the 1999 independent elections in East Timor, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua have been resolved so far, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims of the Paniai shooting welcomed his claim with disbelief.
"I've been questioned four times in the last three years, but I haven't seen anything yet," Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
A few years later, he is still living in fear.
"I'm afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid the army will arrest me or someone will shoot me."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many residents of Paniai, who are worried about the incident.
According to him, he was beaten by members of the army after he helped bury four of the victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the army began to look for me," he said.
And the shooting hasn't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in neighboring Deiyai.
A skirmish in which one person was killed and another 17 were injured occurred between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to provide assistance in transporting a man unconscious to the hospital.
Ravianus Douw, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company building.
According to the police, villagers threw stones at the officers and the answer was a warning shot.
But locals say a mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) started shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
"There was panic, we were afraid of retaliation," said 29-year-old Domingu Badii, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the arrival of the wounded.
"I haven't left the house for two days."
The Deiyai parliament demanded the punishment of the police officers involved and the withdrawal of the mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a thorn in the eye for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the separation of the indigenous peoples of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes who live in the central highlands.
Many have joined the Papua Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of insurgents that protects the rights of Papuans by attacking and kidnapping Indonesian police officers.
Some of the leaders of OPM come from Paniai. These include Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of the attacks in recent years, the army has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of residents of Paniai, all under the pretext of "ensuring national sovereignty".
Some of them will never be seen again.
Paniai is known among the inhabitants of Papua as a "tragic and forgotten place".
Poverty adds oil to the fire.
The little rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
The bread is unreachable.
The locals grow their food: mainly sweet potatoes, fruits and leafy vegetables.
Women work in the fields; each of them cultivates four or five fields with sweet potatoes.
Most of the harvest is intended for the needs of the family, the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten pieces of sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Since Nabire airport opened more air routes and new immigrants began flowing into the country, there has been an increase in economic inequality between native Papuans and immigrants.
Already so few jobs are usually filled by more educated and wealthier immigrants.
Papuans rarely have the capital and education they need to get into business.
“Young people are moving out of villages due to lack of jobs and money,” said John Gobai, chairman of Paniai’s tribal council.
Thanks to isolation, the province of Papua is hidden from the world.
Strict rules for foreign journalists also contribute to this.
Earlier this year, two French journalists - Franck Escudie and Basile Longchamp - were expelled from Papua New Guinea for "lack of cooperation with the authorities", despite the fact that they had been granted such a rare permission to film.
Phelim Kine, deputy director of the Asian branch of Human Rights Watch, Jokowi, in his election campaign promised to abolish strict rules for journalists and achieve transparency and development, but this never happened.
“Foreign journalists working in the rebellious easternmost regions of Papua and West Papua are at great risk: non-recognition of visas and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of reports from foreign journalists means that international pressure on Indonesia in the Papua case is largely limited.
In March, six Pacific nations — Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands — urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “various and widespread acts of violence” in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also supported the OPM in the past.
Indonesia’s foreign ministry spokesman, Armanatha Nasir, dismissed the accusations when he told reporters in Jakarta: “Indonesia still has a democratic system and the media is free, so it is difficult to disguise evidence of human rights violations.”
Local people are calling for the participation of foreign governments.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, headed by human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, locals called out, according to a source who also attended the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous, the slogan “we want freedom”.
In 2019, Indonesia has another election planned, but the Papuans say they won’t vote for Jokowi.
"Jokowi is a man of good intentions, but surrounded by people associated with the Paniai shooting," said Gobau, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai - in addition to living in constant fear of a looting army - are lurking in poverty, miserable education and the health system.
Gobai claims that the inhabitants of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote to be a "debt" that must be repaid to Jokowi.
“They don’t want money, they want justice,” he added.
Despite the threats and intimidation of the families of the victims of the Panai shooting, they continue with the last symbolic act of defiance: they bury the bodies of the victims on the plot opposite the police and army station.
Knowing that justice will never be done enough, at least it will not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
"A member of our family has been killed," Yacobus said with his head down.
"What can we do?"
