The Torch skyscraper burns in Dubai for the second time
In Dubai, one of the largest residential skyscrapers in the world caught fire on Friday, with firefighters having to evacuate all residents of 337 meters high and 79-story buildings.
In the last two years, this is the second fire of this high-rise building, which bears the appropriate name The Torch.
All residents of the building were evacuated and there were no injuries. The cause of the fire is unknown.
“We were asleep and the alarm woke us. We heard screams.
It took us ten minutes to get down from the 50th floor,” said Geroge, one of the skyscrapers’ residents.
Dubai Civil Defense said firefighters managed to get the fire under control around 4 a.m. (00 GMT) and continued to cool the building.
Government officials added that they are providing replacement accommodation for the affected residents.
The incident could once again spark a debate about the safety of materials used to lining high-rise buildings around the world.
The results of the investigation that started the construction of the Torch skyscraper after the fire in 2015 showed that the most damaged were the cladding and external panels used for decoration or insulation.
British police said the grenfell tower's insulation and lining system could have contributed to the rapid spread of fire in a June fire that killed nearly 80 people.
