EPA chief Scott Pruitt postpones Obama administration emissions reduction directives
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by 15 states, its chief, Scott Pruitt, revoked his earlier decision to postpone the implementation of the former Obama administration’s plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt has introduced changes to his plan to respond more rapidly than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
He did not, however, mention a legal challenge against his previous position in the Federal Court of Appeal.
This refers to the latest deadline set for 1 October, when states should begin to comply with the 2015 regulation to reduce the amount of ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the deal by one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid “interference with local decisions or imminent economic growth.”
Pruitt, who served as Oklahoma’s state attorney general before President Donald Trump’s appointment as EPA chief, has long served as a staunch opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industries.
Wednesday’s sudden turnaround is the biggest legal setback for Pruitt’s regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA executor exceeded his authority in an effort to delay the Obama administration’s inclusion of a plan that required oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt proposed his version of ozone standards and strengthened the EPA’s commitment to working with states through complex processes and meeting new standards within a given time frame.
“Under the previous administration, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines and waited to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set up the plans,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
“We don’t believe in regulation through litigation and we take deadlines very seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes from it.”
However, the EPA said Pruitt could use “the possibility of delay and all other legally available authorities” at some point to ensure that regulations “are based on sound policies and the most available information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a more comprehensive rewrite of ozone rules.
The White House budget approved last month seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet passed the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed a coalition of states suing the EPA this week, said the group was not going to allow legal coercion.
“The turnaround in the EPA’s views – following our court case – is an important victory for the health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by air pollution,” Schneiderman said in a statement.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone is created when common pollutants emitted by cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants, and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious respiratory problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists are appreciative of Pruitt’s sudden change.
“It’s worrying how much pressure needs to be exerted to change the mindsets of responsible people and protect the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to fight the ideological campaign of the Trump administration, which seeks to help polluters and special interests.”
