China is lacking in tourists.
Beijing is losing billions due to visa policy.
For decades, China has been trying to exert its influence without the use of force.
It spends ten billion dollars a year supporting language schools and building universities abroad, pushing its entertainment industry to foreign markets and trying to attract Western tourists.
This is not happening in Beijing.
Local state media talk about a plan to turn tourism into a driving force for economic transformation and modernization.
However, the number of arrivals increased by only 3.8 percent last year, and about 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.
This is due, among other things, to the fact that, despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, the situation in the world’s most populous country is assessed by Professor of Economics from the University of Beijing Christopher Balding in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for itself is China’s visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free travel with China, while the citizens of the other countries have to settle their visas in advance.
In the U.S., crowds are comparable to Chinese New Year celebrations.
The visa costs $140, but if you don’t want to wait for it for long hours in a queue, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such constraints create significant economic barriers.
A study in the Journal of Economics and Finance found that visa requirements reduce a country’s number of visitors by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China’s gross domestic product and is home to less than one percent of its population, was visited by 1.8 million Americans.
China often exacerbates the problem itself when it uses tourism to pursue its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China cut traffic to South Korea in the spring as part of a rift over South Korea’s missile defense system, the South Koreans retaliated and avoided China.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent year-on-year, while Japan saw an increase of 85 percent.
This affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recent report by the US central bank, the Fed may have left China for as much as $190 billion as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China receives about $35 billion a year as part of the sale of currency to incoming tourists.
According to official balance-of-payments figures, China had a deficit of $217 billion in tourism last year, equivalent to 44 percent of China's total surplus in trade in goods.
Thus, the small number of tourists to the country, which anxiously prevents the outflow of capital, is inflicting a very painful blow.
However, the above-mentioned factors are only one manifestation of a more general abstinence towards foreigners.
In many parts of China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
In 2013, there were fewer than a million foreigners in China.
There are more of them in the United States and some individual cities.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has doubled.
A number of scientific papers show that immigrants tend to revive economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
You will not find them in China.
It will be politically challenging to solve these problems, but the step that is being proposed is to simplify the visa system.
Other Asian countries, particularly India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to simplify and reduce the cost of visa procedures.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currencies, it should be easier for them to get there.
