Moore's Ford Bridge Massacre: Activists Recall Racist Lynchings
A 1948 Ford Mercury drove past the spectators of Monroe, Georgia, and curled towards Moore's Ford Bridge.
But before a car with four black passengers and a white driver could reach the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked his way.
The leader of the group, a middle-aged man in a striped suit, pulled his cigarette for a long time and stared at the windshield of the car.
Inside, the passengers trembled with fear.
"We want that n--- Roger!" the man shouted.
"Bring it to me!"
Silence is broken by the roar of a young black man who is pulled out of the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this scene is a mere reconstruction of the events that took place on July 22.
But when one of the men throws the rope over Roger's neck, the audience sighs with excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists have regularly returned to Moore’s Ford Bridge to reconstruct the fateful night of 1946 when two black couples – Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Mae Murra Dorsey – were killed by members of the Kukluxklan.
No one has been tried for the murders yet.
“It’s amazing that no one has been arrested in all these years – even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identities,” said Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the reconstruction of the event.
"It is a stain on our history and a burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and a lifelong civil rights activist.
In his eyes, the reconstruction of the event presents a dramatic call to action. Every year, he reminds the Monroe community that justice has not been done enough.
“We demand prosecution and closure, peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all,” Brooks said.
"Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin."
On July 27, 1946, a coroner covered one of the bodies of the victims of the lynching at Moore's Ford.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were to take part in the lynching.
However, no one has been prosecuted so far.
Despite the fact that the suspects remain at large for decades, civil rights advocates claim that the two reasons for the lynching - politics and sex - were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court of Georgia granted blacks the right to vote in elections scheduled for the summer for the first time.
And it was during the summer election period that black farmer Roger Malcolm was supposed to stab white landlord Barnett Hester during a skirmish - allegedly because of his wife.
According to Brooks, it was a tradition in the city that Hester had been hanging out with Malcolm's wife, Dorothy, and had brought her into a different state.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison filed a $600 bail against Malcolm.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and his cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
On their way back from prison, just outside the entrance to Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects blocked their way.
"As it turns out, the murders were planned and orchestrated by Harrison," she said.
“It is also clear that there was a collusion between state and local law enforcement officers who not only took part in the lynchings, but also disposed of evidence and concealed the identity of the witnesses.”
Brooks made a brief statement on the matter.
“It was a massacre because of the right to vote,” he said.
“The murders had a clear subtext for all black locals: ‘this is how you end up if you register and go to vote.’”
The annual reconstruction of the event at Moore’s Ford Bridge has been organized by Cassandra Greene for almost a decade.
Her performance is figurative, engaging and concise, showing a deep-seated racism that many would like to consider extinct in modern America.
Watching this reconstruction is not easy, and it is even more difficult to turn your eyes away, but Greene says it makes sense.
“Nobody wants to talk about lynchings because we have to face the unpleasant feelings that are hiding in each of us,” Greene said.
"But we can't have a relationship unless you listen to what I've been through."
The main rehearsals of this year's reconstruction began in June, and on the first day about 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest blacks - flocked to the room where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh is an assistant director.
He played the leader of the Kukluxklan for many years, but in his words, the role is exhausting.
"I have a bad feeling about it because it contradicts who I am," Marbaugh said.
“I think it’s very important to remember this part of history on a regular basis because we never want to go back to that time.”
Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, rehearse their roles.
The show begins with a skirmish – Malcolm argues with Hester and blames him for sleeping with his wife.
"Get out of my land n----e!"
You can't do Rascon.
There's a skirmish.
At that moment, everyone (at least every black actor) will explode in laughter.
Greene laughs the most.
"What happened?" Rascona asked.
He's confused.
Was I being too rude?
"No," Greene replied cheerfully.
"I just don't think white people used to say 'n--r' in that tone."
'Exactly, 'said one of the black actors.
"You have to put more emphasis on R."
The energy in the room is suddenly better; hostility will replace the feeling of closeness.
Everyone wants the show to be authentic, just to make it worth it for the four victims of the massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
This time Rascona emphasizes the correct pronunciation of the word with N.
No one laughs anymore.
The show ends violently and quickly.
The screams, the shots... and the silence.
A woman dressed in black stands above the bodies of the actors and sings the mournful song of Billie Holiday "Strange Fruit".
With every word, there is sadness in the room.
Against the backdrop of all this, about a dozen spectators wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
In the audience there are practically the same number of blacks and whites.
One couple traveled all the way from Ithaca, New York, many of the spectators are from nearby.
Each of them endures the local humid climate for almost eight hours, and Brooks leads them in a crowd to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until now, murders could have been viewed at a distance, but now, standing in the same place where the lynchings took place, the atmosphere is frightening.
With the final words of the song, Greene summons the crowd to inspect the bodies.
The children kneel to the heads of the victims, watching the fake blood and immobile bodies and whispering something to their ears.
'They're not dead, 'said the little boy.
After a few minutes, Greene will thank the audience.
The actors clean the rope and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw embraces Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the leader of the Kukluxklan.
Nick Rascona embraces his two fellow actors and weeps in their arms; eventually, emotions overwhelm him.
"It's all right," one of the women whispers.
"We know you're not comfortable with that role.
But you had a reason.”
Later that day, the audience sits down with the actors for dinner.
At one table, a young white couple talks passionately about a performance with a black couple they met today.
Denise Duplinski could hardly find words to express her feelings for today's performance.
"It's hard to listen to the ugly words and look at the ugly acts... that people do who look like you and do it because they look like you," she said of the reconstruction.
“It makes me realize that lynching is still a topic,” she added, “just called police skirmishes.”
On the other side of the room, Tyrone Brooks is sitting in the courtroom, enjoying dinner while talking about civil rights.
According to his own words, he has already started planning the show for the next year.
“The reconstruction of these events is inspiring because it describes the fear we had to experience – but it’s also a moment to think about,” he said.
"If we don't learn from this, who knows... it could happen again.
People who do not know and study the history of their country are doomed to repeat it.”
