The latest results of tests to determine the age limit of asylum applications in Sweden
The latest results of tests of asylum seekers in Sweden who have been subjected to a new method of assessing their age show that over 80 percent of people were asked as older than 18, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Agency (R<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xA4>ttsmedicinalverket) started carrying out new tests earlier this year.
The aim of the method is to assess applicants more accurately in the context of the assessment of asylum applications. The measure was taken after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who had lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has submitted 6,880 cases for investigation, and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests carried out between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were judged to be over 18 years of age, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency judged the interviewee to be "possibly over 18 years of age".
In another 423 cases, it was decided that the interviewee was “possibly under the age of 18.”
Tests are only taken if the age of the interviewee is disputed.
According to Johan G<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xB6>ransson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
“As compared to last month, the statistics are kept in a tight track and the numbers are very similar,” he told The Local.
A higher number of applicants whose age has been estimated to be over 18 years does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers are lying about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said that in 442 cases it was found that “the person interviewed is 18 years of age or older”.
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the interviewee stated that he would be 18 years old this year.
The medical method of determining age, which includes x-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of the knee joints, which are subsequently assessed by dentists and radiologists, has also received criticism.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, which, among other things, is engaged in assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age of puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue and I don’t think these types of measurements to assess age are correct.
The assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we can’t determine the age with accuracy, we shouldn’t pretend otherwise,” he told the Metro newspaper.
The forensic medical agency Agency's G<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xB6>ransson defended the decision, saying: "Generally speaking, the risk of misjudgment of a child as an adult is low.
The highest risk is the fact that the person interviewed is just under the age of 18, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of all respondents.
