NHS Prescribes Controversial HIV Drug to 10,000 Patients
From September, patients will have access to ‘transformative’ treatment for HIV prevention based on the Supreme Court’s decision to fund the NHS drug.
The National Health Service (NSH) announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients over a three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to fund the probationary period after an appeals court upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year stating that the NHS had the funds to pay PrEP despite saying the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, which was announced on Thursday, was accepted by NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a “significant intervention” while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a “decisive moment”.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Other clinics will join in October and will be fully implemented across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission between at-risk patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there is a sufficient amount of specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who sign consent to participate in the testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status has not yet been checked by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program comes to taxpayers at <0xC2><0xA3>10 million and the NHS of England signed a contract this week to distribute drugs after winning an international public procurement.
The trial period is designed to collect clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and fully utilize the ever-expanding and increasingly successful HIV prevention efforts.
It is another milestone in more than 30 years of efforts to halt one of the greatest challenges to human health.
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National AIDS Trust, said: “We are witnessing a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
If administered correctly and to patients at risk, PrEP will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
From September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We welcome this statement with pleasure.”
Ian Green, CEO of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “The number one priority must be fast testing across the country; we must make it accessible to every patient.
We now have the PrEP trial drug available and are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.”
Shadow Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start testing across the country as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and, together, to end the spread of HIV in society.”
High-Level Life: Mezzanine and Smart Design Turned This Small Apartment at Earls Court into a Spacious Home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for real estate, traded a large house in Knightsbridge for an apartment on the Earls Cour in 2014.
Located on the first floor of the Queen Anne smart terrace - it is a vivid example of modern design that makes the most of available space.
“I used to live with my ex-husband in a much larger house in Knightsbridge,” Joanne said.
“I was looking for something at a reasonable price.
I bumped into this apartment in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I immediately fell in love with him, and the same day I nodded at him.”
Since then, the apartment of 1000 square meters has undergone a complete renovation.
One-room apartment with a complicated layout - to get to the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - Joanne wanted to add storage spaces and a mezzanine to make use of the high ceiling.
“I longed for a high ceiling, big windows and a lot of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
For this purpose, she employed Erfan Azadi of the Duck & Shed design studio based in Notting Hill and used the nearly four-meter ceiling to create a home that was not just a project, but also a place to live.
The ceiling was not high enough to fill two gaps - the challenge for architects was to create a mezzanine on which to walk upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
"The steel structure is quite complicated," he explained.
"We had to arrange both spaces so that we could walk upright.
It was not just to build a simple platform, but at the same time to bend the steel structure so that at the correct height above and below the ceiling."
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on top of each other - and at the same time add to the drama.
The mezzanine overlooks the beautiful living room with old copper window frames in Retrouvius design.
Mirror furniture in gold, silver lines and a retro chandelier by Serge Mouille create a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short corridor is equipped with mirrors on both sides and looks longer.
The mirror bar in the kitchen looks like a window to the next room.
At the front door there are storage spaces equipped with mirrors for storing cutlery and glasses.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of a significantly larger space, is the ability to separate it from the kitchen, if not used.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
However, what is unique about this solution is the folding door.
"We had to solve the technical side," Erfan says of the reinforced veneered doors.
"The door is counterweighted so that it can be pushed back very easily."
Thanks to the clever use of space and storage space, Joanne gained an additional 16 square meters, a second room and a better overall layout of the apartment.
"When it comes to that, what you're selling is living space - or valuation of your property," Erfan said.
"A real broker basically calculates the price of the apartment on the basis of living space when entering the apartment."
In this case, it was possible to increase the living area while preserving high-quality materials that give the space a luxurious appearance.
“Material is very important because you touch it and create an emotional bond with your home,” Erfan added.
“You won’t love the electricity in the walls.
Yes, they’re important, but they won’t win your heart.”
As it turned out, the quality design and increase in living space can turn an ordinary apartment into an exceptional work of art.
And just like Joanne, you can finally decide to stay.
