Trump's new chief of staff plans to cut the president's media diet
Many have tried it before him and have always failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
If so, it will be the first.
The new White House chief of staff plans to restrict the flow of President Trump’s information – including reports on television news – in hopes of keeping Trump afloat.
Here's part of reporter Josh Dawsey's report:
“When the new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly met with the staff on his first day in office, he outlined a key problem Trump’s White House is going to fix: misinformation that gets into the hands of the president.
Kelly told employees that he must personally approve all information – whether on paper or verbally – because the president can make a better decision based on the right information.”
Kelly’s diagnosis makes sense, but many of his predecessors have broken their teeth to check on Trump and his presentation in the media.
Trump’s relationship with the media dates back decades — and now, sitting in the White House, his habit of watching TV news is even stronger.
“If Trump, as a candidate, was upset by the honest reporting, it was appropriate to show him that he was being talked about in a positive light by many other media outlets that were easier to convince,” Sam Nunberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri of Politico wrote at the time that “the key to keeping Trump’s tweets in check – at least according to six former campaign organizers – is to ensure that Trump regularly watches the media praising him.”
All right. Okay.
But the idea that Trump’s tendency to post his views on Twitter has ever been “under control” is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaign organizers know something that others don’t – that Trump’s tweets would be more outrageous if they weren’t checked.
The tweets that Trump never tweeted will most likely never be heard.
If his employees managed to keep him in check at least a few times, then their efforts did not go to waste.
But no one has been able to regularly prevent Trump from sparking controversial topics.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, which is made up of rival factions, people regularly try to bolster their agenda by pushing Trump’s materials — which may or may not be reliable — to support their worldview.
In May, Politico, which covered the issue from all sides, published a report on the tendency of advisers to submit questionable information to the head of state.
Here is an example of such information from the pen of reporter Shane Goldmacher:
Current and former Trump officials claim that the president is often very angry at negative media reports, especially reports of leaks, and seeks to find their origin.
The situation came about in late February when someone planted a copy of an article from GotNews.com – the website of provocateur Charles C. Johnson – that accused Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being a “source of many leaks” from the White House.
Notwithstanding the fact that Johnson has been permanently expelled from Twitter for harassment; or that he has not substantiated his claim with any evidence; or that he has published false accusations in the past and later retracted them.
Trump read the article and started asking about Walsh.
Goldmacher added that then-Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House Secretary Rob Porter were “trying to implement a system to manage and document the information President Trump receives.”
Would it work?
Now, three months later, Kelly is trying to enforce the same strategy.
