The murder of a journalist highlights the growing threats in Mexico
Riodoce's staff meets regularly every Wednesday to discuss news about the unrest taking place in the Sinaloa area involving organised criminals, corrupt officials and endless drug wars.
Today, however, under the onslaught of recent events, they meet mainly for their own safety.
They learn that it is important for them to change their habits.
Two well-deserved journalists talk about what would be safer: taking their children to an office that was attacked with a grenade in 2009 or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three simple words on the blackboard: adversaries, neutrals and allies.
They ask journalists to give names for every word - no evidence is needed, just use imagination and foresight.
To pick them out - drug traffickers, politicians, traffickers and journalists are suspected of taking money from the government or drug cartels - a catalog of criminals tasked with covering up criminal acts.
The violence continues and the bodies pile up across the country; journalists are constantly growing among them: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, there have been at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 journalists are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and seven have been killed in all seven states this year.
Among them is the co-founder of Riodioce, editor and inspiration for colleagues, Javier Valdez Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and work as a journalist,” Valdez wrote in one of his many books on drug-related violence.
His loss is palpable, even though his presence is pervasive - a large picture of Valdez with the inscription "Justice" pointing to the middle finger hangs on the front of the building; two journalists - Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez - over 30 years old, have a T-shirt with a photo of Valdez with a smile on his face, his face and his glasses on his nose.
The meeting takes place less than two months after his death; journalists talk about mutual trauma, nightmares, insomnia and paranoia.
Despite the fact that a special federal prosecutor's office was set up in 2010 to deal with journalists' cases, it has so far sued two suspects, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
Most of the thousands of murders that occur each year are linked to drug trafficking and organized crime, making it very rare for journalist killers to be brought to justice.
The journalists from Riodoca insist on reporting on the violence that is taking place in Sinaloa; even though they are devastated by grief and the said territory is very treacherous at the moment.
Without information about the killers and without a vision of justice, a security meeting is pointless, Ibarra says.
"It's foolish to waste time on such meetings," he adds.
“If we don’t get more information, we can’t trust anyone.”
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left Riodoce headquarters in Culiacán, the capital of Sinaloa.
He managed to drive a few blocks when his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men who pulled him out of the car and killed him with 12 shots, apparently because of the title of the article - which can be translated as the Twelfth River.
The shooters then got into his car and hit him not far from the crime scene.
Valdez died at the age of 50.
He left behind a wife and two adult children.
Rumors seem to be spreading fast in Culiacan.
However, in the case of Valdez, there is a suspicious silence.
Since Guzmán’s arrest last year and his January extradition to the United States, Sinaloa has become one of the country’s bloodiest battlefields as rival factions try to fill the void.
Every day, several people are killed on the streets of Sinaloa, and the cemetery is full of jeweled two-story mausoleums for drug kings, many of which are larger than houses.
Forget for a moment that the word “armistice” means that one drug cartel controls a coastal state with precious ports and important routes through which drugs travel to the United States.
Despite the fact, as well as the fact that Valdez was intimately acquainted with the risks of his job, Ismail Bojorquez, 60, co-founder and director of Riodoce, still resigns from not protecting his friend.
He believes that two mistakes contributed to his death.
The first was the February issue of an interview with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival drug cartels that waged war on the sons of Joaquín Guzmán.
The reconciliation might have angered the sons; the suspected gang members had bought all the copies of the newspapers as soon as they landed on the shelves.
The second mistake was not to force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after the seizure of other newspapers with the same story.
Valdez has become a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his death is seen as an important milestone in the struggle of Mexican criminals against journalists.
He managed to survive for so long, and all his friends and colleagues believed that this would never change.
In the periodical Noroeste, he was practically a veteran when in 2003 he decided to sell his $50 shares and found Riodoce together with five colleagues.
In Sinaloa, “it was impossible to do journalism without mentioning the drug trade,” Bojorquez said.
Riodoce eventually gained a good reputation for brave and truthful reporting; the newspapers began to thrive.
Journalists liked to search for problematic topics and publish texts without censorship - readers were fascinated by reading stories that no one else dared to publish.
Eight years after its founding, Riodoce won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Award for its coverage of Latin America.
In the same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists for his brave reporting on the Mexican drug trade.
Valdez openly admitted that he was afraid.
"I feared for my life," he said as he received the award.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is a “way of life,” Valdez said in an interview with Rompeviento TV in October last year.
"You have to take on the role of a journalist - or play dumb.
I don’t want anyone to ask me, ‘What were you doing in the face of death... why didn’t you tell me what was going on?’”
Riodoce employees miss Valdez. The man was known for his jokes and indiscriminate language. He was a good friend who liked to give advice and hugs - a teacher who knew how to survive.
They were all relying on his daily routine.
He always wore his hat.
He often went to the El Guayabo bar opposite the offices and sat at the same table.
Now they ask: did this routine cause his death?
His death also raised questions in them about their own assumptions - how to do their job best and stay alive?
“They don’t like it when you get involved with their wives, their kids, their clean shops, their secret landing pads.”
"These things were forbidden," Boyorquez said.
As a result, there is a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
If you feel that something is wrong, take your hands off.
The problem, Riodoce editor Andres Villarreal said, is that “smell is a sense that can be fooled... and then there’s that thing with Javier.”
The old rules, he said, no longer apply in Sinaloa – as in the states of Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak governments and corrupt politicians.
The landscape is constantly changing.
No mobile phones are allowed in the Riodoca staff meeting room because a few days ago a spyware was discovered that governments were buying to monitor Mexican journalists and activists.
In front of the building, two police officers find relief from the forty-degree heat in the shade of a nearby tree.
They were chosen by the state to protect the offices of Riodoce, which are located in a four-story building in the bourgeois district of Culiacan.
Journalists joke about whether these police officers are among the 50 percent of law enforcement officials who are corrupt, according to the government.
It has been several months since the last time journalists traveled to mountainous areas that are essentially controlled by drug cartels.
There are three main stories on the agenda this week.
The first of these is the murder of the brother of former boxer Julio César Chávez in Sinaloa.
They also dealt with suspicious government spending in the governor’s hometown.
Recently, there have also been several kidnappings at one of Culiacán's most luxurious restaurants, just a block from the state's attorney's office.
Officially, no one has disclosed the identities of the kidnapped people or the circumstances of the kidnapping, so journalists were alert when they were about to write about what every city dweller knows: that that restaurant is a favorite destination for drug dealers and politicians.
One journalist read from public records that the restaurant was registered under a name associated with a certain politician who is a member of the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), controlling all levels of the political scene for almost the last century.
Several PRI governors have recently been charged with high-level corruption.
Villarreal asked journalists to write about earlier incidents that occurred in the restaurant, including an incident in which one of Joaquín "El Chapo" Guzmán's sons escaped the army's intervention unit.
A month ago, readers would have read about it in the Valdez section, which was the best source of information on kidnappings.
"Valdez would certainly solve the case," said Villarreal, 46, who is nicknamed "El Flaco" for his slim figure.
"Now all the informants have turned their backs on us."
Valdez's office has turned into a warehouse of signs and stickers to protest the killing of journalists. Employees certainly did not expect them to become activists in the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez grabbed several signs and went out the next morning to demonstrate in front of the prosecutor's office for another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared just three days after Valdez's murder in the western part of the state of Michoacán.
Only a burnt body was found, and the authorities say that based on the DNA analysis, it's Adamea.
The activity of journalists is intensifying throughout the country, many of them organizing protests and drawing on the sidewalks and buildings of the "SOS press".
The director of the newspaper Bojorquez is on a visit to Washington, D.C., where he seeks international support and justice for Valdez's death.
At a meeting with Governor Sinaloa the day after the murder of Valdez, Ramirez accused the authorities of monitoring journalists and their murders for proclaiming the truth.
In the meantime, she asked to be transferred to another department for fear that her anger could jeopardize her impartiality.
Valdez has repeatedly said that Mexican journalists are “overtaken” by organized crime, corrupt officials and an indifferent public.
In his latest book, Narco-Journalism, he wrote that journalists are dying not only at the hands of drug cartels, but also at the behest of politicians and security forces who cooperate with organized crime.
The media watchdog group Articulo 19 has accused police and public officials of more than half of all attacks on journalists.
"You're going to die in Mexico because they want to silence you," Ramirez added.
Murders obviously work.
No one will forget the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macías six years ago at the northern border of Tamaulipas.
Her body was found along with a note allegedly signed by the Zetas cartel: “This is how I ended up because of my messages.”
Next to the decapitated head lay a keyboard and headphones.
Some branches have decided to shut down, such as the newspaper El Norte, which is based near the northern border of the state of Chihuahua, in response to the March murder of reporter Miroslava Breach.
Others still continue, just as El Manana of Nuevo Laredo did after the assassination of their director in 2004.
In 2010, the Diario de Ciudad Juarez addressed drug cartels publicly with an article on the front page titled “What do you want from us?”
Some journalists have fled their homes or even crossed borders.
It's a difficult decision.
Finding a job in exile is difficult, as well as getting rid of the feeling that you are constantly being pursued.
And journalists are being harassed and killed, as in the case of Ruben Espinosa, who was murdered in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico City, three months after fleeing Veracruz.
For those who choose to stay and not give up their job, every day is a great risk.
Ibarra, who once wanted to be a poet, admits that writing about drugs scares him.
“Mexico is going to hell, that’s why I became a journalist,” he said.
