Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however frightening.
Researchers have now uncovered the first findings of an astonishing rhino-sized creature whose perfectly preserved remains — which experts have dubbed the ‘Mona Lisa of Dinosaurs’ — have been found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were preserved to such a high degree that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of his scaly skin and reported that the dinosaur had a “problematic past.”
An article in the journal Current Biology said it was “the best-preserved ever found armored dinosaur and one of the best dinosaur species in the world.”
The Dinosaur lived during the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
His perfectly preserved condition literally shocked the researchers, who described him as “really remarkable.”
According to National Geographic, the armored squirrel is the best-preserved fossil of its kind.
Shawn Funk discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He stumbled upon what appeared to be an alien object and decided to examine it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers spent the next six years working to uncover an animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1,100 kg.
After the work is completed, the dinosaur is ready to be discovered.
‘Just close your eyes a little and you’ll believe he’s sleeping,’ said Caleb Brown, the head of the work and a naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
‘It will certainly go down in history as one of the most beautiful and well-preserved dinosaur species – the Mona Lisa dinosaurs.’
By studying his skin, researchers found that this herbivore — despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank — was likely facing a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a camouflage system used by many of today’s animals.
Experts say that this allowed him to better blend in with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The camouflage system suggests that he was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
Reports of the 110 million-year-old dinosaur Nodosauridae family first appeared in the newspaper in May. It is currently available for viewing at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who spent more than 7,000 hours with the team carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the patterns and shape of scales and armor throughout the body.
They uncovered a method of camouflage commonly used by today’s animals in defense – the animal’s upper part was darker than its lower part.
Although this camouflage effect is common in nature, the researchers’ findings are surprising, as Borealopelta’s size far exceeds today’s animals using the same technique.
It is therefore possible that the dinosaur was so many predators that evolution preferred disguise over confrontation in survival.
Many modern animals with camouflage - for example, a deer, zebra, or beltfish - are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus had to literally fight for its survivors.
“The sale of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur illustrates the dangers that predators posed during the Cretaceous,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic components contained in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur skin was likely reddish-brown.
Researchers continue to study the animal and search for more knowledge about its life, including the preserved contents of the stomach, to track down its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur fell into the river after death and was carried away into the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
The area of Alberta had the same climate as Florida at the time, and the rivers and oceans stretched farther inland than they do today.
“This nodosaurus is really remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin and at the same time it is preserved in three dimensions so that we can see its original size,” Brown said.
“For these reasons, the animal looks practically the same as at the time of the Cretaceous.
