How did one activist learn the answer to the question: ‘Whose Streets?’
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell shook her entire body.
A day after arriving in New York, a St. Louis native sat down on the bed in an Airbnb room and scrolled through Facebook posts on her phone.
She came across a contribution from a high school student.
"Police have just shot an 18-year-old boy whose body is still lying on the street," it said.
She was surprised that no one else wrote her this post, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
<0x40>TheePharoah kept retweeting her wall posts.
A St. Louis rapper tweeted about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old who was shot dead by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's body lying limply in the street, from which no one had taken him even after four hours.
"That's crazy," Ferrell thought.
Death was nothing new to her and her family.
She put down her phone to come back to him the night she watched tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
One of the men claimed to be the victim’s father, holding a sign in his hand that read “Ferguson police killed my unarmed son”!
She was watching the live news - one of the policemen stood in front of a group of protesters, holding a leash in his hand and a barking dog at the other end.
In another video, another police officer, she said, held a gun in his hand, pointing at the crowd and shouting, “I’m going to kill you all...the animals.”
"That's not normal," Ferrell said to herself.
"This is not the kind of murder we're used to and what we can call normal.
I felt goose skin all over my body.
"I was angry and I was crying."
She immediately booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11:00 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided to leave for Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years is described by a new documentary, "Whose Streets?", which will be released on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and resistance, of strength and tenacity, told from the perspective of people living in a community who go out into the streets and demand answers.
On her way to Ferguson, Ferrell initiated a dialogue with her daughter - dressed in a floral jersey and the same floral headdress - on a topic they had discussed many times before - "about the experience with blacks."
"Remember when I taught you how black people had to fight for what they believed in?" she recalled.
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and that's not right."
"There was no way I wouldn't take her with me," Ferrell said later.
“Today’s events are the culmination... of what has happened in the past.
She had to know and see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
She needed to develop not only in activism and organization, but at the same time she had to know the difference between the different layers of experience with blacks and what we have to do to liberate ourselves.
Despite the fact that I am able to provide her with conditions in which she will not experience racism on her own, she is in no way different from another black child-woman.
I feel that if I could protect her from this experience, I would only harm her.”
Upon arrival in Ferguson, the first stop of the South Florissant Road was opposite the police department, which became the base of activists who were waiting for Darren Wilson's words about his possible involvement in the incident.
Here Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who was preparing food for the others.
Together they prepared food in bags and helped to deliver it to the Protestants.
A new type of activism was slowly emerging in Ferrell’s eyes.
“My activism turned upside down after August 9,” Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was the president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. association and sought to introduce health care and food in black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural."
A few weeks later, Ferrell met the later co-director of the documentary, Sabaah Folayan, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "just document" the ongoing events.
Ferrell asked, “Are you working on a documentary or are you trying to find a story that can be used?”
This type of skepticism penetrated the community through many people, often whites, who wanted to make money on pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in an unanswered interview, “We’ve heard that the voices of people who are born and raised in Ferguson are very often overlooked, and that’s what we wanted to change.”
Folayan has already established a collaboration with co-director Damon Davis, a renowned local artist who deals with the subject of prisoners in the cell of death.
Ferrell and six other locals, who were followed by the Whose Streets? team in the years following Brown's murder, were also involved in the project.
"No one speaks for us in this documentary, but it's our testimony," Davis said.
"It was important to me - how these people will be represented - because in the same way I will be represented."
While the purpose of the documentary was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences - in an attempt to show that the movement "is not about a savior leader, but about bringing the community closer together," Folayan said - it turned out that she was the most open to participating in filming.
“Whose Streets?” describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell’s life, such as how she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt naked," said Ferrell, smiling at the first moment she saw the final version of the document.
"But I realized that in order to do this job and humanize blacks, I had to open up."
In addition, Ferrell’s story highlights the role of the eccentric black woman in the broader aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement — who created a social media campaign under #BlackLivesMatter in response to the 2012 murder of teenager Trayvon Martin — call themselves weirdos.
“Black eccentric women in leadership positions ultimately stand for preserving the movement,” Ferrell said, “because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must bear the brunt of these events."
Folayan agrees with this statement, adding that “the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of eccentric black women.”
She insists, however, that "this is not a mere affirmative matter" and Ferrell is not the main heroine of the documentary because of her views.
"She was the driving force and source of energy," she said.
“It’s no coincidence that she’s at the front lines, because life at these crossroads in the skin of a black weirdo woman is dangerous.
You can feel the energy in front of the screen.”
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, television cameras have cleared their positions, but heavy racial ties between the community and the police persist.
Ferrell is serving a two-and-a-half-year sentence for blocking a highway during demonstrations.
She described the social-political atmosphere in the area, which she calls home, as "a mess."
Yet she does not cease in her efforts, to which she has been committed since she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
The only thing we have to lose is our chains.”
