A Becoming Resemblance: Artist Creates Portraits Using Chelsea Manning’s DNA
In the center of one of the rooms of the Fridman Gallery in New York, there are several faces of different skin tones - white, black and gray - hung from the ceiling on the wires, each of which seems to have fallen out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from smears from her mouth and hair, sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where she is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized disclosure of classified cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which was launched on August 2, is called A Becoming Ressemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her expertise in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before he left office.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning’s DNA and using 30 portraits to depict what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual commentary on the suppleness of DNA – as well as on the many ways DNA can be interpreted – and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, had been talking about herself as a woman since she was young, and was convicted in 2013 of 20 charges, including six espionage laws violations, computer fraud, and theft.
All of her photographs were held by the prison staff, and only one black and white, lower-quality photograph leaked to the public, in which Manning, visibly concerned, sits in the driver's seat in the platinum blonde wig she is now associated with.
In 2015, there were still positive reactions to the 2012 project Stranger Visions by Dewey-Hagborg.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic items – such as cigarette butts and chewing gum – to create a picture of the possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
“They were about to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to add a portrait to the article,” Dewey-Hagborg said at the opening of the new exhibition.
Visits and photography were not allowed, so they asked Chelsea if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoila Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
Indeed, a few days after the comic was published, President Obama asked for Manning’s release, a welcome change after several unbearable years in a Kansas military prison.
What’s really interesting is that the exhibition takes place at a time when Donald Trump is at war with people who seek to expose government information and transgender soldiers, while trying to find new ways to incite resentment in areas he should support.
Dewey-Hagborg said in response to a question about this particular timing that “everything happens for a reason.”
Under the artist's statement on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls out with her huge signature (the letter "i" in the surname is leaked with the heart) after the end of "self-sacrificing factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture."
On the opposite side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a centipede of the letters C, G and A recorded with a pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist’s sophisticated scientific vocabulary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
“I hope that people will learn from this that our genome does not matter who we are and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way,” said Dewey-Hagborg.
“DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them.”
The last copy of the exhibition, placed in a separate room, is the only page from the above-mentioned graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging in the manner of King Kong from the United States Disciplinary Barracks with a megaphone in her hand.
“Once they stop you from speaking, they win,” it says.
"Never be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript of one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning had not yet personally visited the exhibition - as predicted in the comic book - but when she did, she would be welcomed in the center of the room with her masks, her own genome-like images, arranged like a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the almost 160 cm tall statue of Manning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded with a pencil.
"In the past, they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted to make them feel crowded," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
“I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates it.”
