Startups to help your company avoid becoming the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the employee satisfaction of her e-commerce startup, but couldn’t find a suitable survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And despite promising anonymity to the survey, some employees expressed their distrust of the whole process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, owner of the San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
He asked for help from outside.
New HR startups are constantly emerging on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intention of measuring employee responsibilities, startups allow companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographics, offer complete employee anonymity and a complaint hotline, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass supervisors and contact directors directly.
“There are tools on the market like Strava and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of the Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that thanks to Glint, she has gained more awareness of what her employees think and feel in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and voting of specific teams, Glint offers a temperature map of the company and an overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of managers with low ratings - allowing the user to work on the remedy.
Companies are beginning to realize the need to look out for the culture of the workplace – in case they become another Uber – that is sweeping through scandals after a former employee posted a blog post describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the technical and financial progress website Let’s Talk Payments, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
The Denver, Colorado startup Convertent, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before Uber’s scandals.
Nearly 600 of Convertent’s clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has also taken under its wing.
Like Glint, Convertent allows companies to send customizable “flash” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
Where the Director-General is involved, complaints are sent directly to the Management Board.
“The Court of Public Opinion has regulators empowered,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
If a company is convicted of ill-treatment of its employees or unethical behavior — and if regulators do not intervene — it may face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotts, employee exhaustion, or court proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convertent for more than a year to raise employees’ awareness of corporate policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate leadership.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to trace the phone number or e-mail to the management of the company, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
It was often a deterrent and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday’s general representative, who said there had been no reliable way to track employee complaints before.
Now that the company uses Convercent, it ensures rapid detection and resolution of problems that previously never got to managers sitting in offices, miles away from real complaint resolution - for example, discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
“It’s approaching a holistic, overall view of employee experience,” said Vitrano, who heads Ruby Tuesday’s risk management group.
“At the same time, we protect shareholders from employee litigation.”
Companies stopped taking ethics, values, and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron collapsed in a case of employee ethics abuse, Quinlan said.
But it wasn’t until “social media lit up the whole thing” that companies began to realize that in the online world they couldn’t just hide their skeletons in a closet.
“Before humans started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith,” Quinlan added.
Both Glint and Convertent offer their software in the form of a service for which the company pays regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity endorsed by bold capital investors who have supported both startups.
As part of its February campaign, Convertent raised a total of $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and eventually withdrew a capital of $47 million.
Glint earned $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and earned $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing number of surveys clearly confirm that today’s employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, the main advantage is not high salaries and interesting projects.
Employees want to feel that they are being accepted and appreciated and that they are dedicating their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
“If people are happy in their work, they feel that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they are striving for the success of the company,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses both Convertent and Glint.
Investors make money if a company thrives, and companies thrive if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market that ensures employee engagement and commitment to the company, it is not surprising that there are many investors who will support this effort.
According to experts in work culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is useless if the company does not take the necessary steps.
The fact is that once a company requests feedback from its employees, there can be big changes.
And if the change does not happen quickly - in the worst case at all - it can provoke disappointment and disinterest of employees.
“Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations,” said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, who has witnessed many companies relying too much on data alone.
“Because as soon as you don’t get things done, employees start asking themselves, ‘Did they hear me?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, why should I care?'"
Madison Reed, which now regularly surveys employees every month, can solve the problem within a day with Glint, Errett said.
After collecting feedback from employees who were frustrated with slow decision-making and quality communication, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start communication training to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday gains a very important view of its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in a field known for frequent layoffs in the long term.
“If you don’t seek to create a transparent work environment, employees won’t believe you,” Vitrano added.
“And as soon as you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company will go bankrupt.”
