Facebook Plans to Examine Facts More Thoroughly to Reduce the Number of Fake News
Facebook will send more potentially fake articles to third parties to check and display the findings below the original posts in an effort to combat so-called “fake news,” the social network said on Thursday.
The company says in a statement on its website that it will begin using updated machine learning to detect possible hoaxes, which it will send to third parties for verification and potentially display the survey results under the original posts.
Facebook has been identified as one of the main sources of fake news, and many believe that these unconfirmed reports influenced last year’s election of the President of the United States.
Political debates are taking place in Europe, with French voters flooded with fake news about the presidential election in May, and Germany planning to impose a fine on the social media network ahead of the September election if it does not swiftly remove angry posts.
Facebook said in a statement on Thursday it was planning to test a new fake news check feature in the United States, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
“In addition to displaying third-party verified messages, people are asking for more content to be better informed and to be able to make the right decisions about what they can share,” Sara Su, Facebook’s product news manager, said in a blog post.
She added that Facebook is continuing to test the “related articles” feature and is also working on other changes to reduce the number of fake messages.
Creating a graphic novel: the story of A Castle in England
Scotney Castle recently starred in the music video for Squeeze, and Margaret Thatcher took refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
Scotney, however, witnessed 700 years of tumultuous history from his cosy little town on the Bewl River in Kent, UK, which inspired the curly Jamie Rhodes of York County - known for his fondness for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
“The sight of the writing of a man who is 300 years after his death fascinates me,” Rhodes says with a serious face.
"When I hold a letter in my hands, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of the families who lived at Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, this is not Rhodes' first book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection of documents inspired by the British Library - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was fascinated by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like going back in time.
I love the archives!”
For someone so fascinated by old papers, the support from the National Trust and the Arts Council of England and the possibility of staying almost four months in the castle is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, going through the archives, and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on the wall and bottles that had been thrown in the trench for centuries.
He strolled through the property and explored the ruins of the old castle, talking to the hawkers, gardeners and occasionally the artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
At night, he drank whiskey and wrote.
Scotney's confidential history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust gained access to the documents only in 2006 after the death of her last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site ten years later, the workers were only beginning to penetrate the archives, which Rhodes described with words such as "aristocrats of many centuries throwing their hands with the words: 'Take it to the attic.'"
Journals, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing property: "You may think the land dispute is boring," Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were fighting over a birch tree.
Stop it, people!"
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the 1381 English Rebellion.
"I found a record of a mutiny at a castle in 1380 called the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex," Rhodes said.
“The English uprising actually started in this area, and I thought the uprising was a good starting point.
Maybe they have something to do with each other after all.”
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by Darrell's family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was only discovered a few years later after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes’ favorite family are the Darrells: “I was intrigued by the male generation – men back then were always indebted and spending money on things they couldn’t afford.
Various generations of the Darrell family have dealt with this by marrying rich or old mistresses—I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to shake the heads of the heirs.”
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes searches for further adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stand in the Finnish wilderness, where he drew inspiration for his next book on Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was engulfed by nature.
This is a strange place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
“I was like, ‘Now I’m going back to real life.’”
