Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can alleviate symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million U.S. residents and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to consume meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms. However, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
Study leader Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that support tolerance and protect the body without damaging the sensitive tissue.
Once the scales tilt to the side of the inflammation, an inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells supporting the body's tolerance in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan, one of the building blocks of protein, to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We found a link between one species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support the body’s tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had.”
At the same time, he suggested that if the same was true for humans, then a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, as part of a study of a certain type of immune cells supporting body tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice bred separately lacked cells.
One group of mice has a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
Intestins of mice were tested by DNA ordering method, and the researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells that were lacking in a second group of mice.
Mice that were kept in a sterile environment and lacked an intestinal microbiome -- so they didn't develop this kind of immune cell -- were injected with L. reuteri bacteria and developed immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers cultured L. reuteri in a fluid and then transferred small amounts of the fluid — bacteria-free — to underdeveloped immune cells that were stored in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the number of these cells increased by 50 percent.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us store L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the byproducts of tryptophan from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: “Each of us should probably strive for the development of these cells, because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestine.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may increase the cell population."
