White House Props Cost Taxpayers Thousands of Dollars
The decision by the White House to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry last month came at $24,000, according to Navy records published by the weekly TIME.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the President on board, was the highlight of the July 17 program at the White House, which was a parade of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several high-ranking White House officials watched a showcase of products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was on display next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck and a forklift from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the helicopter's presence less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - the unit responsible for managing the helicopter - said in a statement.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy's deputy commander for aviation, the day before the event began.
The report suggested that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. for the occasion of the show, which is scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and remain on site until the entire site was completely cleared, which was scheduled between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m.
The e-mail also said that if there was a delay on departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for the return flight due to working time regulations.
The original crew remained on site that evening, along with the helicopter and a security unit.
From the records - obtained by TIME Weekly - it was not clear whether a second crew had been sent in the end.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government assets for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this regulation.
"We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was in order," the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you've been blocked," the deputy commander replied.
This "Made in America" show was designated by the White House as an official event and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political implications.
While attending the event, the president pushed for a health reform that passed through the Senate and spoke of trying to keep the government's decrees in check.
The use of aerial vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence purely for presentational reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane rolled in the background at his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is flooded with complaints about his predecessor’s use of the presidential plane.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ show, which unveiled products from all 50 states that are made by Americans from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, deputy press secretary.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often practice landings in the Washington area and on South Lawn, and rehearse possible arrivals with the President of the United States at the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump was attending the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 exercise landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the crew's current training, the official said.
The helicopter unit flew on the same day as part of “non-presidential support missions” for another eleven hours.
The White House said no additional props were paid for with taxpayers’ money.
A Sikorsky spokesperson said the company was not in any way involved in the negotiations to put the helicopter on South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights, and the exact costs associated with the parade are difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017 is $24,380 per flight hour for DoD expenses for the VH-3D.
The unit records the time 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below the stated amount.
"It is very misleading to state taxpayers' costs based on estimates for reimbursement of expenses," Walters said.
“These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual costs.”
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD expense reimbursements do not include personnel costs, but include fuel costs, maintenance and contract costs.
White House Press Secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the purpose of the parade.
“The idea of the show, which is taking place this week, is to introduce products made in the US,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to the defense of our state and that they are providing jobs to hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens are involved in.
This fact should be remembered.”
It is not clear whether Trump was also looking at the helicopter during his tour of South Lawn. The only thing that can be said with certainty is that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House, Trump approached a Sikorsky representative and joked with the media about his own product fleet.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the President, "I own three."
